-1 BACKGROUND2~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|                 Extended Background Advice                          |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

In devising your character's background, here are a few things that
you should think about:

- At its most basic form, a background tells about your character's
past, showing the events that molded him/her into the person they
are today.  The more detailed backgrounds will even foreshadow the
character's future development, and give immortals possible hooks
for helping the process along.  It's generally a wise idea to add
notes about the important events, detailing how they affected the
character.

- Your character's background doesn't stop when he gets taken over
by a player.  If an important event happens to your character
during gameplay, it's always good to add it in.  A dynamic background
helps facilitate a dynamic character.

- Length: There is no set length for a background, and as indicated
above, we even hope that the length will change over time.  Should
you run into a problem with length, we recommend that you summarize
your background in the space provided, then provide a URL with the
complete version at the bottom.

- Style: Given that the background has its roots in narration,
questions about the style of presentation will naturally arise.
There have been numerous different kinds, such as journals, 
narrative tales, first and third person, and so forth.  While
none are inherently better than the rest, be sure that in
choosing your style, you choose one which will properly display
as many facets of your character as possible.  If necessary, add
in extra notes at the end, just to be be thorough.  (Note: Should
you decide to do a story, be sure that it has more relevance to
your character than just having his name in it.  Reading long,
pointless stories rarely brings a smile to immortal faces.)

- Spelling/Formatting: No matter how hard I try, I always have a hard
time taking a poorly written background seriously.  Seeing spelling
errors every other word, or even just seeing a huge, two-page chunk
of solid text without paragraphs, is usually enough to make me not
want to take the time to examine the thing carefully.  Using the
"bg format" command will help you immeasurably, so long as you
remember to hit enter twice to demarcate a paragraph.

- Originality: While the presentation doesn't have to be too special
or elaborate, the character itself should be.  Don't be another evil
person that killed his parents, or another Duddly Do-right that had
his parents murdered by shuddeni.  Even being something as simple as
a common soldier can turn out to be more refreshing and more
interesting than the stock melodramatic fantasy set-up.
~


-1 MERCY GRANTMERCY BEG~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\
|   MERCY                                                             |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Usage: mercy [death/beg/force]

By using the mercy command, a player can specify under what conditions
they will spare the life of a foe.  Using 'mercy' by itself will
display your current settings for granting mercy.  If you grant
mercy to your opponent, they will be held under your blade, and
able to do only a small number of actions.  Attempting to murder
someone who you have in such a state will immediately result in
their demise.

'mercy death' will toggle whether or not you will hold back on the
              death-dealing blow to a foe.
'mercy beg' will toggle whether or not you will grant mercy to an
            opponent who 'beg's for it.
'mercy force' will toggle whether or not you immediately finish off
              a foe you have granted mercy to if you are attacked
              by another.

A player may use the "beg" command to beg mercy of an opponent
who they are fighting, even if the deathblow is not imminent.

The "grantmercy" command will release a victim who you have at
your mercy.

Let it be known that at times the best of intentions will go
awry, and the deathblow cannot always be held back, particularly
when dealing with magic.  Gladiators, experienced in the ways of
such fighting, suffer less from this problem than others.
~

