-1 CHESSRULES 'CHESS RULES' 'RULES OF CHESS'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|          Rules of Chess                                             |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Chess is a game played on an 8*8 grid of alternating black and white
squares. Players begin with two rows of pieces, each placed on an
opposite sides of the board. The chess board at the beginning of the
game appears as follows:

a   b   c   d   e   f   g   h
  ---------------------------------
1 | R | N | B | Q | K | B | N | R |
  ---------------------------------    White:
2 | P | P | P | P | P | P | P | P |    Player1
  ---------------------------------
3 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |    Black:
  ---------------------------------    Player2
4 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |
  ---------------------------------
5 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |
  ---------------------------------
6 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |
  ---------------------------------
7 | P | P | P | P | P | P | P | P |
  ---------------------------------
8 | R | N | B | Q | K | B | N | R |
  ---------------------------------

It is currently white's turn to move.


Different letters represent different pieces, which have distinct
movement patterns, and all have distinct methods of removing opposing
pieces from the board. 

The abilities of the chess pieces are summarized in help 
CHESS PIECES. Read this now.

In chess, the two sides, white and black, each take turns.

By tradition, the person playing white goes first. 

On each turn, a player may move one and only one piece, subject
to the constraints in help CHESS PIECES. 

The object of the game is to place the opponent's king in CHECKMATE.

We say that a king is in CHECK if on the current state of the board,
the king can be captured on the opponent's next turn.

We say that a king is in CHECKMATE if it is in check, and no move
the king's owner can make will take the king out of check.

A player wins if he can put an opponent's king in checkmate.

There are other ways for a chess game to end:

The game ends in a draw if:

-Both players agree to a draw
or
-A given board pattern repeats three times in a row. (This is meant 
to indicate that the game is stalled) 
or
-It is clear that checkmate cannot be forced (i.e., two kings remain)
or
-Stalemate: An opponent's king is not in check, but he cannot move the
king without placing it in check, and the only possible moves available
to the player involve moving the king.

~
-1 'CHESS PIECES' CHESSPIECE~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|        Chess Pieces                                                 |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

We refer to chess pieces by the symbols used by the game. (Read help
CHESS RULES for a picture of a chess board).

P: Pawns
Pawns are the most basic unit in chess. Pawns move forward, one 
square at a time, toward the opposing player. On their first move,
pawns may optionally move forward by two squares. Rather than 
moving, a pawn may opt to capture an opposing pieces which are 
diagonally forward and adjacent to the pawn. 

Thus, if we had:

K * B
* P * 

The pawn in question could either move forward, or opt to capture
the opponent's Knight or Bishop. 

Pawn's also have two additional special properties:

(1) Pawns which reach the eighth row of the chess board (i.e., the
opponent's back row) become queens.

(2) En passante:

The following special case allows one pawn to capture another by
moving diagonally onto the square behind another pawn.

Suppose:

(i) A pawn moves two squares forward.
(ii) An opposing pawn is located horizontally adjacent to the final
location of the pawn that moved two squares.

then, and only then, can the opposing pawn take the other 'en passante'. 

To illustrate:

Suppose we have:

* P *
* * *
* * p 

Then, the owner of pawn P takes his turn:

* * *
* * * 
* P p 

Then, the owner of pawn p may take P 'en passante':

* * * 
* p * 
* * *      

Notice, p moves diagonally behind P, and captures P. 


R: Rooks

Rooks begin the game in the upper or lower corners of the board. 
Rooks move horizontally or vertically (but not both at once), and may move as many squares forward or to the side they wish until they encounter an obstacle. Rooks capture opposing pieces by moving horizontally or vertically onto the square of the opposing piece.

N: Knights

Knights begin the game in the squares horizontally adjacent to the rooks. Knights move in an 'L' shape fashion, moving either 
one square horizontally and two vertically, or two horizontally and 
one vertically. Any opposing piece on the square the knight lands
on is captured.

So, if we have a knight:

* * * * *
* * * * *
* * N * * , the following are all possible knight moves:

* N * * *   * * * N *   * * * * *  * * * * *
* * * * *   * * * * *   N * * * *  * * * * N
* * * * * , * * * * *,  * * * * *, * * * * * 

B: Bishops

Bishops begin the game horizontally adjacent to the knights.
Bishops may move diagonally as far as they wish (but not in both directions at once), until they encounter an obsctable. Bishops
capture opposing pieces by moving diagonally onto the square 
located onto the opposing space. 

Q: Queens

Queens begin the game horizontal adjacent to the bishop and king.
Queens can move horizontal and vertically like a rook, or diagonally
like a bishop (but not both at once). Queens capture in the same 
fashion as rooks or bishops. 

K: King

The king is the most important chess piece, as its safety determines
whether the game is won or lost.

Kings move just like queens, subject to the caveat that they only move
one square at a time. 

Kings, unlike other pieces, cannot move into a position of danger.
A 'position of danger' is a location on the board where the opponent
could take the king on their next turn. In chess parlance, kings
cannot 'move into check'.

The game is won when the opponent's king is in 'check' (in a position of danger), and no move the opponent makes can take the king out of check (checkmate).

Kings cannot be captured: only placed in check, or checkmate.

Kings have a special move available to them, known as 'castling', which
involves the rooks. For a king to castle, the following must be true:

(1) Neither the king or the rook may have moved this game.
(2) All pieces horizontally between the king and rook must have moved,
leaving the squares blank.

Kings can castle on their side, or the queen's side.

King's side castling occurs as follows:

The king moves two squares toward the rook.
The rook then moves one square past the king, on the side opposite

Thus:

* * * * K * * R  (before castling)
* * * * * R K *  (after castling)


Queen's side castling occurs as follows:

The king moves two squares toward the rook.
The rook then moves one square past the king, on the side opposite the
rook's previous location.

Thus: 

R * * * K * * * (before castling)
* * K R * * * * (after castling)

Castling is carried out within the game's chess engine by 
instructing the king to move two spaces to the left or right.


~


