-1 NAME NAMES~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|        Names                                                        |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

When you enter Avendar, you should realize that you are assuming
the role of a fantasy character (as outlined in help ROLEPLAYING).
In keeping with this notion, you should choose your name accordingly.
Your name should be an appropriate for a fantasy roleplaying
environment. Here are a few guidelines to help you along the way:

-The name should not be a dictionary word

Reason: This is a fantasy world. We aren't really meant to be 
speaking English. If you want your name to mean something, dream up
a word and say that it means this in the fantasy language of your
choice. Names like "Twist" or "Claw" don't add anything to
the experience - rather, they indicate a fixation on the 
ordinary.

-The name should not be a recognizable character in an existing
work of fantasy. Avendar is an original world, so we expect the
characters in that world to vie for originality as well. It's also
very disconcerting to see Elrond the barbarian, Gandalf
the shuddeni swordmaster, or Rand the Srryn bandit

-The name should be appropos for a fantasy setting. This means we'd
like to avoid such real life names as "Bob" or "Joe", and instead 
focus of names more suited for quality in a fantasy world. This also
includes names in other langagues that aren't suited to Avendar. 
(i.e., names like "el chupacabra", etc.)

If you're having a problem dreaming up names, consider checking out
EBON: The Ever Changing Book of Names, located at
http://www.utu.fi/-sapyorre/ebon/ 
(That - = a tilda....), which is a superb(!) program for Win 95. The
page also has links to other name generators, if you have a machine
that doesn't support EBON.

In the future we'll be offering EBON files for each of the major
languages of Avendar, so  you can get a feel for the languages.
(We even use EBON to help us name some of our own mobs)

If the immortals find your name inappropriate, you will be asked
to change it. Rather than having to do this, however, try to
adhere to the guidelines given above, and spare us all some time.

~

-1 ALIGNMENT2~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|        Alignment2                                                   |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

To give you an idea how various alignments behave, here are a series of
hypothetical scenarios, and some typically responses from various 
alignments/ethoi:

Suppose that a party of adventurers come upon a town, which is being
raided by goblins from a nearby dungeon. The townsfolk, in dire need
of help, beg the adventurers for assistance. 

A lawful good would probably agree whole-heartedly. Towns and cities
provide the most protection from the innocent, and therefore need
to be defended. He or she would probably help the townsfolk organize
their defenses in a more coordinated way. Failing this, he would try
to organize retaliatory strikes against the goblins.

A neutral good person would also agree, but might consider more options.
He might be more concerned with directly fighting the goblins (such
as leading his group to fight them), rather than protecting the
fabric of the town itself.

A chaotic good person would agree, but we might go about the problem
in radically different ways. He would be far more concerned with
getting rid of the evil threat (goblins), than he would be protecting
the laws and walls of the township. Their means of finacing their
quest might be a touch unorthodox as well - stealing from evil citizens
of the town, or a wily plan to trap the goblins.

A lawful neutral person would probably do what he could to protect
the town. The preparations he employed might be similar in form
to that of the lawful good person, but he would be more concerned
with protecting the integrity of the town and its capacity to function
as a society, rather than individual innocent lives.

A true neutral person would be inclined to consider the offer very
carefully. He would most likely be more concerned as to the reasons
for the goblins raiding. Has the town recently infringed on the
territory of the goblins? Or have the goblins grown out of control
recently? The answer to these questions will heavily influence the
nature of the response. They might prefer not to intervene, not
wishing to upset the delicate balance that might exist between
the townsfolk and the goblins. Or, they might decide goblin
in the activity in the region is too high, and needs to be curbed.
They might even see that the townsfolk are being too aggressive in
their exploitation of the world around them, and *they* are the ones
who need to be foiled.

A chaotic neutral person's response is perhaps the most difficult
to predict. They would most likely go along with the opportunity
for further adventure, but if the person had been doing a lot of
goblin hunting lately, the prospect of helping the townsfolk might
not appeal to him. He might, for a lark, side with the goblins if they
would have him - not out of malice, but merely for a change of pace!


A lawful evil person would look for appealing methods to turn the
situation to his advantage. He certainly would only help the 
townspeople fight off or attack the goblins if some reward or other
sort of compensation were offered. Depending on the predilictions
of the person in question, they might even take this opportunity
to try to insinuate himself into a position of power within the
township. And, if the opportunity presented himself, he might
also not be averse to assembling and controlling a goblin army . . .

A neutral evil person would size the situation up carefully.
Which side would have the most to offer him - the townsfolk,
or the goblins? Who is most likely to win? Would it be more 
profitable to just sit back and let them fight it out, and take
on whatever faction was left in the end? Regardless, the neutral
evil person's actions would be completely motivated by their own
self interest, with no concern for the others involved.

A chaotic evil person would most likely side with the goblins if
at all possible. The idea of aiding someone just because they
asked them (an admission of weakness) would probably be anathema 
to them. While if a large reward were proferred they might attempt
to destroy the goblin, but they would be more likely to try to
pocket the money and run, or let the goblins burn the town, then
kill the goblins.


