-1 ALIGNMENT ETHOS~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|          Alignment and Ethos                                        |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Characters in Avendar choose both an alignment and an ethos upon 
creation.

Your ALIGNMENT is a measure of your character's moral compass.
Your alignment can be good, neutral, or evil.

If your character is . . . 

GOOD, he or she will tend to not place their own interests above
those of others. 

NEUTRAL, he or she will tend to not take a firm moral stance.
They might choose to distance themselves between the turmoil that
surrounds the fight between good and evil, or to crusade actively
to promote a measure of balance.

EVIL, he or she will tend to act in whatever they perceive as
their own best interest, regardless of the cost to others.


ETHOS:

Your ethos determines their attitude toward laws and
the nature of society.
Your ethos can be lawful, neutral, or chaotic.

If your character is . . . 

LAWFUL, he or she will tend to follow the established rule of
law. Lawful characters are typified by the idea that for whatever
reason, society should in general be governed by a code of laws,
and that they personally should do their best to exist within
the confines of these laws.

NEUTRAL, he or she is indifferent to the laws and rules of society.
There actions and attitudes toward the laws will depend more on
their other beliefs rather than any explicit opinion for or against
the law. 


CHAOTIC, he or she the laws of society as a whole as a hindrance
to their beliefs or goals in life. Chaotic individuals tend
therefore to place more importance on the ideas and opinions of
individuals, and to place their faith more in chance and fortune
rather than order and pattern.


For more help on alignment and ethos combinations, see the
following help files: LAWFUL GOOD, LAWFUL NEUTRAL, LAWFUL EVIL,
NEUTRAL GOOD, NEUTRAL NEUTRAL, NEUTRAL EVIL, CHAOTIC GOOD, 
CHAOTIC NEUTRAL, CHAOTIC EVIL, ALIGNMENT2

~





-1 'BECOMING AN IMMORTAL'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|          Becoming an Immortal                                       |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Characters who have reached the 51st rank ("hero-rank") may petition
to become an immortal.

The job of immortal is not one embarked upon lightly. It requires
an enormous amount of patience, and having the sense of self to handle
long hours of thankless work and/or abuse from the people above and
below you. 

This being said, these are the things we tend to look for in applicants:

-Creativity: Nothing is more important than the capacity to create
 new ideas. 

-Roleplaying: Your character should have to demonstrate the ability
 to not only play a fantasy role, but also to play one -well-.

-Knowledge of the World: Your character should have acquired a 
 certain level of understanding of the way the world works, 
 the classes do/do not balance, and what is/is not possible 
 with the class they've played to hero.

-Participation: We want to see characters who have gone out of 
 their way to contribute to the world that is Avendar. This 
 includes things such as being a part of quests, accomplishing
 your own character's goals with respect to the world, and 
 overall being a part of the overreaching conflicts in the
 world.

Now, as for the application process itself, after you have become a
hero, and you think you're ready, here's that you need to do.

Step I: Write an Application

Your application is a note you write to immortal. The note should 
be out of character. When writing your application, try to answer
the following questions:

-Why do you want to be an immortal?
-What do you think you have to offer the imm staff here at Avendar? 
-How long have you mudded? What sort of experiences do you have
 elsewhere, either as an immortal or as a player?
-How do you think your character's role has changed from its
 original inception? How do you think you've fulfilled the goals
 set out for your characters?
-What's your vision of the future of Avendar? What would you like
 to change, if you could, and how would you go about changing it?

Once you've answered these questions, you should include your
design for an area for Avendar. This doesn't have to be anything
super detailed, but it will serve to let us get an idea of your
creative potential, along with what sort of ideas you have. 
This are isn't necessarily the first are you will write, and may
never be created at all, but having an idea that we -would- consider
using goes a long way. In fact, the more thought you put into this,
the more impressed we will be with your application in general. 

Finally, you can insert whatever other things you feel are important
to your application. You can include things like signifigant 
accomplishments, a history of your time here on Avendar, or the like.

Now, once you've done all this and sent it in a note to IMMORTAL,
wait for our decision.

If we like what we see, you'll go on to Step 2. If we don't like
what we see, we'll try to tell you what our problem with you or your
application was. Only in exceptional circumstances will you be 
allowed to reapply with this character. If you didn't succeed,
try to remember that it takes a lot of time and experience, and
not everyone has the fanaticism or dedication it takes to run a MUD.

Step 2: The Interview

If we've found your application satisfactory, we'll arrange an
interview between you and the Implementors, along with what other
immortals have an interest in your case.

The interview is meant to be a final trial by fire of the soul of
the applicant. The interview will be out of character, but do 
expect to defend any and everything about the role your character
has played. Expect questions about your ideas and opinions, as 
well as questions about your proposed areas. 

If you survive the interview with your soul intact, you will
then become an immortal.

If you do not survive the interview, the discarded husk of your ego
will be returned to the real world, where you will gibber the
Truths of Elder Things madly until the end of your days.

Good Luck!

~


-1 REALISM REALITY~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|            Realism                                                  |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

A natural question that arises in the construction of any artificial 
gaming universe is what degree of realism one wishes to impose on
thid universe.

It is our contention that the proper attitude to employ is neither
a slavish devotion to 'realism for realism's sake' nor a complete 
abandonment of the idea that we are in the business of creating 
a cohesive fantasy environment, but rather, we should strive for
a "suspension of disbelief" that is so coveted in other media.

Our goal is to create a world that abstracts the essence of a 
grand fantasy. Imagine your favorite work of fiction (most particularly
a work of fantasy), and the odds of part of why you enjoy it is that
it draws you in s very wonderful way into the author's world.

Imagine walking the halls of the Mines of Moria, or a force march
across the Blight, seeing the world from the back of a flying Tarn,
or even riding into battle with the knights of the round table. 
Take those emotions, and those experiences, and that strikes at 
the essence of what we're trying to create, except we hope to 
make our _own_ world, where people can have these sorts of adventures.

The realism that we have tried to incorporate into the world is 
a slave to the larger goals outlined above. Realism isn't pursued
as a thing in and of itself - rather, as a means to the end of 
immersing people in a role-playing fantasy experience. Of course,
this means making things a challenge for players - it wouldn't
be much of a story if the villain is defeated on the first page, 
and there is no test or trial by fire of the souls of the heroes.

Contrawise, we want our players to be concerned with great things,
not petty ones. That's why we don't make you worry about obscure
things like the effect of your character's bathing habits on the
price of bread, or when the last time you stopped fighting monsters
to take a bathroom break. We try to minimize tedium, and maximize
interesting and neat things. (A never-ending process, we might add!

In short, we aim at at a realism that is fantastic rather than mundane,
and one that strives to be wonderful rather than petty, refined 
rather than vulgar - and we hope we enjoy your travels here.

~



-1 IMMORTAL IMMORTALS IMMORT GOD GODS~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|            Immortal                                                 |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The immortals, or "imms" as they are sometimes known, are the 
creators and maintainers of the MUD. The immortals are characters of
the 52nd rank are higher. They cannot be killed by mortals, and
have a wide variety of powers, depending on their position in the
hierarchy (with level 60 immortals, or Implementors as they are 
known, at the top). 

The immortals perform a large number of functions for the MUD, but 
they can be categorized into two chief domains:

I. In Character Functions:

In character, the immortals represent the gods of the world, embodying
timeless virtues, vices, principles, ideals, forces, and elements.
Immortals of the 53rd rank or higher have religions, with active 
followings in the world. As such, the gods are responsible for 
ensuring that their followers carry out the tenets of their ideals 
in the mortal realms. The gods are those who use the mortal realm of
Avendar as a proving ground for their own philosophies and fights, 
and have corresponding powers.

II. Out of Character Functions

The immortals are the people who have created and will continue to 
create the world of Avendar. Immortals are the people who 'build' 
the areas that make up the world. Immortals are also people who 
design the classes and code the skills/spells used by the players.
The immortals also run quests to further immerse, intrigue, inveigle,
and otherwise bring delight to the players. Immortals are also the 
people who make sure the rules of the MUD are enforced.


Some tips on dealing with immortals:

-Remember in your interactions with the imms that ic they are as close
to all-powerful beings as your players will ever see. If you are
with a god, treat him accordingly, or expect a negative reaction
(which can vary depending on the mood/type of deity you're dealing
with).

-When reporting a bug or problem, try to be as accurate and specific
as possible. Report all the relevant details of your problem. Try
not to get upset or be impatient - the immortals are people too, 
and often deal with multiple bug reports of the same bug, often 
each from a more incensed player than the last. I.e., politeness
goes a long way.

-If you are attempting to contact a god in character, you will have
the most luck from shrines, temples, or other holy places dedicated
to that god. Gods will be more likely to arrange an audience for them,
particularly if you follow the guidelines they recommend in their 
help file.

-If you are caught breaking or attempting to break a rule, honesty
is often the best policy. Trying to lie about what you did will
often result in a harsher penalty, and a more irate immortal.
We do keep logs of the major player commands (such as attacking
other players, logging in/out, etc.), so dishonesty is definitely
*not* the best policy.

Finally, you may wonder how new immortals are created. If you
think you have what it takes and are interested in becoming an
immortal, see the help file BECOMING AN IMMORTAL

Also see:

WIZLIST, RULES, AVENDAR, PRAY, RELIGION

~



-1 DUAL 'DUAL WIELD'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|            Dual Wield                                               |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The ability to dual wield is a skill which classes with at least some
devotion to fighting may master. As its name it implies, it allows the
user to attempt to wield two weapons at once. In order for this two
occur, the following must be true: You must be wielding a weapon in
your "main hand", and have your other hand free (not carrying a held
item. etc.). You then must attempt the second weapon. If the weapons
are compatible, the second weapon will automatically go into your off
hand. If the weapons or not compatible, the second weapon will replace
the first. Compatiblity depends on a number of factors, but a good rule
is that to ensure the proper balance, the second weapon must be two-thirds
the weight of the first. Certain small weapons, such as daggers, are an
exception to this rule. Giant sized races, such as the alatharya, may be
able to dual some two-handed weapons due to their enormous sizes. 
Your skill at dual wield will determine how often you are successfully
able to use your second weapon to hit.
~


-1 MARLAX HONOR 'WHITE FALCON' 'TYRANT OF HONOR' 'FALCON KING'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|           Marlax                                                    |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Note: The Falcon King Marlax is not presently receiving active
followers, as he is on sabbatical from the realms.

Marlax the Tyrant of Honor, Falcon King
"MARLAX" "HONOR" "WHITE" "FALCON"
 
A bearer of the white falcon upholds honor as his or her chief virtue.  
They are self-reliant; they can defeat many foes alone.  While advancing,
they may travel with others, but fighting other adventurers requires even 
odds. They are trustworthy; they will not break their word, and always 
follow any conditions agreed to, regardless of circumstances.  Greed for 
material wealth is frowned upon by those of the white falcon; they take 
only what is needed, and return what is not to the defeated foe.  They 
will not attack an unclad foe, unless they must retaliate against an attack.  
They will only take what they gained in fair combat; theft of this kind 
is severely frowned upon.  Even if your friend is attacked, and slain, 
you must not take from their corpse, unless they were slain in dishonor.  
Finally, they will try to even out odds, if they see many fighting one, 
unless the one is a blood enemy.  Honor is the fundamental issue in their 
victories, whether against evil, or good, or those who don't take such 
sides.

~

-1 EXOTIC EXOTICS 'EXOTIC WEAPONS'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|          Exotic Weapons                                             |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Along with the other major weapon classes in Avendar, some weapons
can not be easily categorized. These weapons, known as exotic type weapons,
can be anything from a net to a rare and unique magical weapon. Most
adventurers will not be automatically be skilled in exotics, requiring
a mastery of their craft before they attain proficiency in them. For
gladiators, however, who train in such exotic styles of fighting in their
arena duels, skill in exotic weapons comes naturally.

~

