-1 EXPERIENCE EXP~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|      Experience                                                     |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Your character advances in power by gaining experience. The amount of
experience you need to advance a level will increase as your level
increases.


You gain experience by:

    Being part of a group that kills a monster
    Gaining mastery of a skill
    Completing certain quests or tasks
 
You lose experience by:

    Fleeing from combat
    Being the target of certain spells
    Dying

The experience you get from a kill depends on several things: how many 
players are in your group; your level versus the level of the monster; 
your alignment versus the monster's alignment; how many of this monster 
have been killed lately; and some random variation.

Here in Avendar, there is an experience bonus for working in a group.
You will receive the optimum amount of experience with a group of 
three, although groups of four or two have been known to be effective.

Additionally, there are some monsters of great power which will take
you much longer to kill than regular foes. If you are successful in
slaying such beasts, you may find that you learn substantially more
experience than is the typical norm.

~



-1 TRIP TRIPPING~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|       Trip                                                          |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Syntax: Trip <Target>

The trip command attempts to bring an opponent down by knocking their
feet from under them. Tripping is most successfully practiced by the
quick and nimble, and fails on opponents who are flying or otherwise
not tied to the ground. Trip can either be used to start a fight, or
in combat, where the argument is optional.

~





-1 STARTING~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|           Starting                                                  |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

As a newly arrived adventurer in Avendar, there are
probably a few things that will come to your attention
starting out.

Q: How do I move around?

A: You can move in one of six directions:
North, south, east, west, up, and down

To move in these directions, type the direction you want to go.

Ex: To go north, type:

North

Q: What if I run into a door?

A: If the door is unlocked, you simply type: 

Open <door's name> 

to open it.

If it's in a particular direction (let's say north), you can type:

Open north

to open it.


If the door is locked, you need to either find some magical way
of going through it, or get the key to the door. Once you DO get
the key, you can unlock the door by typing:

Unlock <door's name>

or

Unlock <direction>


--------------


Q: How do I talk?

A: To say something aloud to the other people in the room,
use the "say" command. 

Example: To say to the room that you're a gladiator, type:

say I'm a gladiator

To send a message to another person, so only they can hear it,
use the "tell" command.

Example: To tell a person named Jolinn that you're a gladiator,
type:

tell Jolinn I'm a gladiator - can you point me to an arena?

Note: For tell to work, two things need to be true:

(a) The person you send the tell to must be logged in.
(b) The person must be visible to you

If you want to _respond_ to a tell, use the "reply" command:

Ex:

If Jolinn tells you 'Any spares?'

You can type:

reply You're a god! Why are you whining for spares?

And it will respond with a tell to Jolinn. The nice part about the reply
command is that you don't need to be able to see the person you're
responding to. This makes it easy to keep contact with friends who might
be hiding themselves magically or through some other method.

Now, in a similar fashion, if you want to send an out of character
message to someone, use the "ooc" command.

Example: To ooc someone that you've got to leave, type:

ooc Jolinn I can't stay - my thesis defense is in 20 minutes!

Just like tell, you need to be able to see the person, and the
person needs to be logged in.

To communicate in a more public fashion, you probably want to use
the "yell" command. Yelling things is like shouting something - everyone
around can hear it. Yelled phrases can be heard everywhere in the
surrounding area (help AREAS) that you're in. In general, unless you
want to irritate everyone in the area, use the yell command sparingly.

Ex of a good yell:
Type:

yell A yithoul dagger for sale, going for 15k gold!

Ex of a bad yell:
Type:

Yell Any sparez?!?!?


Finally, if you absolutely, positively, have to get in touch with the 
immortals, use the "pray" command. NOTE: Read help pray before using
this command. Also, read help pray2.

If you want to pray to an immortal, the syntax is:

Pray <message>

Ex of a Good Pray:

Pray I think I've found a bug with this swordmaster skill.

Ex of a Bad Pray:

Pray He d00dz can I have some el1te sparez!?!?!

Essentially, you should only use pray to report bugs, or to report
observed instances of cheating.



Now that you know the very basics, (getting around and communicating),
you're ready for the next part of the basics, found in the help
file STARTING2

~

-1 STARTING2~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|           Starting, Part 2                                          |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Let's start with the short term things:

Equipping yourself.

To survive, you're probably going to need some equipment.
From the magic mouth where you first arrive, if you head
two north, you'll find yourself at a representative of
the school. If you read the sign ("look sign"), you'll get
some free equipment to get you started.

Don't forget to also get the maps, which will help you get your bearings.

Feeding yourself:

You start the game with 50 gold pieces. The easiest place to buy
food, and a container for water is in the school of heroes. 

If you absolutely must get to the food in the school, here
are the directions from the Magic Mouth at the entrance to the school:

10 north, open north, 2 north, down, east, 2 down, 6 north, 2 east

Your best bet is to stock up on iron rations, and obtain a jug of water.

If you've graduated from the school, and find yourself starving, from
the recall point in Var Bandor:

South, 2 east, 4 south, 4 west, 3 south, east

Remember, the command to buy food is:

Buy <Food item>

In the case of the mercenary in the school, you type:

Buy iron

To eat the food, try: Eat <item>

In the case of the iron rations, it's:

Eat iron

If you're thirsty, you should drink from your jug. Use
Drink <container> or Drink <fountain in the room>

In the case of the jug, type:

Drink jug

Once you get a jug, you might want to fill it with water from a fountain
if you drink all the water out of it.

An easy to get to fountain is:

South, 2 east 

of the Var Bandor recall point.

To fill your jug, type:

Fill jug.

Now that you've gotten your equipment and food, you're ready to make 
your way in the world. Now, you're ready to make your way into the world!

Well, almost. First, you should learn about practicing and training
your skills. To do this, read help STARTING3

~
-1 STARTING3~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|           Starting, Part 3                                          |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/


An important of playing your character is knowing what skills, spells,
and other powers you have available, and know how to use them. 

Firstly, to get a list of the skills you have, type:

Skills

If you're a class with magic, look at your spells by typing:

Spells

These lists give you a list of what skills/spells you have, and
what level you're able to use your spells or skills. 

Most of the spells/skills in these lists has help files, so consult
these for specifics.

However, to take advantage of these skills and spells, you need to 
practice them. To do this, you must go to your guildmaster.

To get to the guilds from the magic mouth, go:

10 north, open north, 2 north, down

This will take you to the hall of guilds, from which you can practice.

Now, let's take an example. Let's suppose you're a barbarian.
From where you entered the hall, you would go east and north, and
find yourself at the barbarian guildmaster.


Now, to learn your skills, you need to practice them.
Type "practice". You should see:

axe                  40% flail                1%  mace                 1%  
spear                1%  sword                1%  enhanced damage      1%  
fast healing         1%  
You have 5 practice sessions left.

This is a list of spells available to you as a level 1 barbarian.

Starting out, you probably want to use a weapon, so it's a good idea
to practice axe.

Type: 

Practice axe

Your axe skill will increase in an amount *depending on your intelligence*.
The most you can ever practice a given spell or skill is to 75%.

As you advance in level, you will obtain more practices. The number
of practices you get *depends on your wisdom*.

Now, you might have also noticed that your character has certain
statistics when you rolled. If you look at the help on STATS, you can
find out what each of your stats is reponsible for. 

Now, the way you normally go about increasing your stats is through the
use of TRAINS. (See help TRAINS) You can train at the same guildmaster
you practiced at. If you type "train" you should see a list of what's
available to train.

Typing train, you should see something similar to:

You have 3 training sessions.
You can train: str int wis dex con hp mana.

You begin the game with three training sessions.

As you advance in level, you will acquire a new training session every
five levels. 

So, to train a stat, type:

Train <stat>

Ex:

Train con

It's a good idea to train your wisdom and constitution early, since
they affect the number of practices you obtain per level, and the number
of hit points.

Ok, now that you've learned about practicing and training, you've done
most of the preparing you need. Now, it's time to learn about fighting,
and some survival tips. For this information, read help STARTING4

~

-1 STARTING4~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|           Starting, Part 4                                          |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Now that you've learned how to move around, communicate, feed yourself,
and practice and train skills, you should now learn about how combat
works.

In your travels in Avendar, you will come upon many monsters. Some will be peaceful, and others aggressive. To kill a creature, use the "kill" 
command.

Example: Suppose you see:

A small lizard is chained to the ground here.

To attempt to kill the lizard, type:

kill lizard

In the fight, if you get in trouble, you might want to try the "flee" command, 
in an attempt to escape. You will flee in a random direction. 

Be warned: Many monsters will follow you, attempting to track you down. 
In order to escape, you may need to employ some magical means of transportation.

One example of this is the RECALL command, which characters of less than
10 th level may use. 

To recall, simply type:

Recall

This will take you back to an appropriate temple in your home town.

Now, when you kill something, you get experience (help EXPERIENCE) for it.
As you gain experience, you will eventually progress in levels.

The best way to get experience, however, is not through killing things
by yourself. As you will learn if you read the experience help file,
you learn more experience from joining a group, optimally one with
three people. 

To join a group, you follow the leader of the group. The "follow" command
will allow you to do this. If, for instance, Jolinn is leading a group,
you would type:

Follow Jolinn

and then Jolinn could add you to his group.

If you're leading a group, use the "group" command to remove or add
someone to your group. Suppose Jolinn is following you. To add him to
your group, you would type:

Group Jolinn

If at any time you don't want to have any followers, type
"nofollow" or "nof" for short. 

To see the status of the people in your group, use the "group" command
by itself. 

If you want to tell your groupmates something, use the "grouptell"
(gt for short) command. This will display a message to only the other
members of your group.

---  

Finally, once you know how to group with people, how do you know where
to go? Well, uses the AREAS command to get a list of areas that are
appropriate for your level range. 

A few good places to start:

-The Tower of Challenges (one south of the magic mouth)
-The merchants around the docks of Var Bandor (if you're good)
-Dogs and Children in Krilin (if you're evil)

Above all, look around, explore, and try asking around, or just
learning by travelling with others.

Best of luck adventuring in Avendar!

For help on other important topics, see:

Help ROLEPLAYING (Important!)
Help PLAYERKILLING (Important!)
Help CHARACTER CREATION
Help HOUSE
Help STONES OF POWER
Help MAGIC
Help RACES
Help CLASSES
Help AVENDAR

~

-1 KICK~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|      Kick                                                           |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Syntax: Kick

The kick skill is an extra attack performed in combat, used for extra
damage. Kick can be attempted each round if desired.

~
-1 DIRT 'DIRT KICKING'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|       Dirt Kicking                                                  |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Syntax: Dirt <Target>

The dirt skill attempts to temporarily blind a person by kicking dirt
in their eyes. Dirt may be used either to initiate combat, or during
it. Dirt kicking will not work in places lacking suitable quantities
of dirt.  (In the air, water, etc.)

~

-1 'FIRST ATTACK'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|         First Attack                                                |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The first attack skill allows one to make one attack a round. This
attack is automatically attempted.

~


-1 'SECOND ATTACK'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|        Second Attack                                                |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The second attack skill allows one to make two attacks per round. Possessing
this skill does not ensure two attacks will be attempted, but it does
increase the likelihood of this occuring.

~
-1 'THIRD ATTACK'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|        Third Attack                                                 |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The third attack skill allows one to make three attacks per round. 
Possessing this skill does not ensure three attacks will be attempted,
but it does increase the likelihood of this occuring.

~

-1 'FOURTH ATTACK'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|         Fourth Attack                                               |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The fourth attack skill allows one to make four attacks per round. 
Possessing this skill does not ensure four attacks will be attempted,
but it does increase the likelihood of this occuring.

~

-1 'BASH'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|         Bash                                                        |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Syntax: Bash <target>

The bash skill is a brute force skill used in an attempt to stun your opponent.
Successful bashing depends on a number of factors, including the size and
dexterity of you and your opponent, as well as skill in bashing. Bash can 
either be used to start a fight, or during combat.

~

-1 MOVEMENT MOVE MOVES MV MVT~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|        Movement                                                     |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Your movement, or moves, represents your character's stamina in travelling
long distances. If your movement ever drops to zero, you will be unable to
move. (Rest or sleep to restore lost movement). Differing terrain requires
different amount of movement to move a single square. 

~

-1 'LIMITED EQUIPMENT' LIMITED~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|       Limited Equipment                                             |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The best equipment here on Avendar is limited. This means there are
a limit to the number of these items that can exist in the world at
any given time. This means that if a mob starts out with the piece of
equipment, if you keep killing the mob, eventually the equipment won't
come back until a piece of this equipment has been destroyed elsewhere.
Due to the power of limited equipment, those below level 10 cannot retain
the equipment if they quit, and it cannot be stored in containers.

~

