-1 COMBINE~

/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|       Combine                                                       |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

This command toggles combine mode on and off. In
combine mode, multiple items of the same type are lumped
into one entry.

Ex: If there are three Yithoul daggers lying on the ground,
someone in combine mode would see:

(3)  A dagger of Yithoul design rests here.

A person not in combine mode would see:

       A dagger of Yithoul design rests here.
       A dagger of Yithoul design rests here.
       A dagger of Yithoul design rests here.

Generally speaking, there's no reason to not be in combine mode,
so unless you have a fetish for spam, it's a good idea to keep it on.

~

-1 SPAM~

/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|              Spam                                                   |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

As you may have noticed, one of our rules is:

*   Unnecessary spamming will not be tolerated.

Just in case you don't know, here's what we mean by spam.
As most of you logged in here are aware, interactive text
based multi-person media applications are a lot of fun, but 
suffer from a number of shortcomings. One of which is the
fact that other users can flood you out of an action by filling
up your screen with garbage and/or useless information.
Your connection really can only support so much information
going either way, so if you receive too much input from the mud,
there's a real danger that none of your output _to_ the mud will
get here. This can be a problem, particularly if your character
is in a dangerous situation (read: most of the time). 

Now, the problem arises when someone maliciously spams you.
An example might be someone typing:

emote slaps you in the face.
Then, repeating this command about 1,000 times, filling up your scream.

Other examples might include (but are not limited too) repeating the same
yell countless numbers of time around town, or sending countless numbers
of repetitive tells to someone.

In short, don't do this. Imms have special monitoring features to tell when
people do a lot of the same command at once, so if one of us is around,
we will most likely notice, and be very upset.

Now, as to the origins of the term "spamming", the term originates 
from a Monty Python Flying Circus sketch (which involves chanting
spam a lot, and repetitively). As to how this first came to its more
general usage on the Internet, this appears to have been lost in the
origins of time.

However, we recommend you consult the Jargon file (available on the web)
for more insight into this and other mysteries.

~



