\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

The followers of Jolinn are marked with the Sigil of the
Sapphire Spear, mark of Jolinn, Father of the Seas and 
leader of the celestial armies of the light.

Followers of Jolinn ascribe to three main principles:

Purity:

Just as the inevitable result of poison is the death of an
organism, so does evil lead to the death of spirit and those
it corrupts. The followers of Jolinn believe that evil must be 
expunged from the land, before it can corrupt and destroy
everything that is good.

Protection:

The things worth fighting for we do so because they are
worthy of our protection. Above all else, the innocent
must be protected against the depredations of those who
seek to corrupt and taint life with their evil.

Unity:

As an overreaching principle, the followers of Jolinn advocate
brotherhood in the light -- both in opposition to evil and unity
in productive effort to aid the weak. Followers of Jolinn are
known for organizing those of good heart, using this unity of focus
to accomplish great deeds.

Known as the Sons and Daughters of Jolinn, those who follow
the Lord of the Sapphire spear are always good, and very seldom
if never of chaotic ethoi. 

Those who seek to follow Lord Jolinn should seek his presence from one
of the holy places devoted to him in Avendar.
~


-1 ROLEPLAYING~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|          Roleplaying                                                |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/


When you come to the world of Avendar, it's a world where role-playing
is not only encouraged, it's required. This means that in any situation
that presents itself to you here, you should do your best to see and
react as an actual person from Avendar would react.This means that you
shouldn't spend your time discussing the real world, but instead
attempting to immerse yourself in the atmosphere of a fantasy role-playing
environment. Think of yourself as an actor, playing a master role in a
great drama. We guarantee this is even more fun than just playing a
'numbers game'. 

For more guidelines, consult the ROLEPLAYING GUIDELINES help file.

For more help on this subject, also see the helps on:
'CHARACTER CREATION' CHARACTERS

~


-1 CHARACTERS CHARACTER  'CHARACTER CREATION'~
/---------------------------------------------------------------------\ 
|            Character Creation                                       |
\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

One of the best ways to think about what you have planned for a character
is to see his or her life as a book of which you are the author. The pages
written with the story of your life, inked in your life's blood. It may
sound a little trite, but if you come to think of your characters in this
way, it's a surefire recipe for role-playing success.

Let's think about the things that a good book has that make for a good
character:

Theme:

Perhaps the most important (and overlooked) aspect of character design is
the theme. What  does it mean for a character to have a theme? It means
that your character has a notion of who he or she is, that this notion is a
definite idea that you wish to explore in the study of your character.

Of course, this doesn't mean that you have to hold to one rigid idea. If
you come upon  something that you think is a lot neater to do with a
character, if you can justify it within the framework of your prior
characterizations, then go right ahead. However, these will be a lot
smoother if you plan them ahead of time. 

Some examples of themes you might want to explore in character design:

Classics:
The Crusader
The Greedy Thief
The Knowledgeable Wizard
The Indomitable Barbarian 

More Difficult (but more rewarding)
The Assassin troubled with the burden of  a Conscience, and struggled with
the implications
of his actions.
The holy templar who doubts his faith, but still keeps the good fight.
The bard who seduces her way to power.
The evil thief who searches, and finds, redemption.
The good warrior seduced by greed, who turns to evil to fulfill his lusts.

These are just examples, but they give you an idea of what a character can
be. And, the more depth you give your character, the more things that are
possible. The character's life is your book, and a good theme is a good way
to start.

Plot:

A book depends on plot to provide a structure and a plan for what the
author intends to show us.  Likewise, your character should have a story.
Questions you might want to answer about your character:

-Where did my character come from in Avendar? 
-What were the factors that determined who my character is today?
-How did my character come to want to/be forced to become an adventurer?

And, once you develop a back story, you need to think about how you'll act
out your characters belief in his or her adventuring career. To make this
interesting, you probably (but not always) want one thing that makes real
books interesting: Conflict.

Having enemies to fight, and challenges to overcome is what makes life
interesting. Unless your character's stated goal is to make friends with
everyone ( a conflict in and of itself, really), you'll end up with some
enemies. Rather than sweating this fact, use it as a source of motivation
and action for your character.

Remember that not all conflicts are vs. other players ^ your particular
character might also be opposed to an idea, and work to change people's
opinion, or even a very difficult locale that symbolizes what he/she feels
is right/wrong with the world.

Characterization:

In general terms, you should work your character function as a real person.
Along with their own implicit philosophy, you might want to give them more
explicit quirks. Maybe your elegant bard has a secret taste for vulgar
peasant wenches, or your dark lord of the void is also an art collector.
Think of the little things that make YOU who you are, and try to think of
ways you can make your character unique.

Tying it all together:

Once you've done all these things, you'll have a character that you will
most likely enjoy devoting a lot of time to. Think of how you might explore
and flesh out your role as you explore. Nothing is set in stone, of course,
but you might consider how your actions tommorow might be dependent on your
beliefs today. And that, in turn, might influence where you'll end up next
week -- the hero who saved the world, or the dark scholar who's one step
away from precipitating Armageddon. Your character is your creation -- try
to make the most of the experience.

~

